### Problem Description

When applying multiple `exclude` query rules, results don't get excluded from results even when they match a single rule.

### Steps to Reproduce

Use at least two `exclude` rules:

```
PUT /_query_rules/vst-curations-sv
{
  "rules": [
    {
      "rule_id": "rule-1587",
      "type": "exclude",
      "criteria": [
        {
          "type": "always"
        }
      ],
      "actions": {
        "docs": [
          {
            "_index": "test",
            "_id": "1"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "rule_id": "rule-9715",
      "type": "exclude",
      "criteria": [
        {
          "type": "always"
        }
      ],
      "actions": {
        "docs": [
          {
            "_index": "test",
            "_id": "2"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

Create some docs to test:

```
PUT test/_doc/1
{
  "title": "hello",
  "tag": "test"
}

PUT test/_doc/2
{
  "title": "world",
  "tag": "test"
}

PUT test/_doc/3
{
  "title": "again",
  "tag": "test"
}
````

Execute a search using the query rules. The rules match the query and they should remove docs 1 and 2:

```
GET test/_search
{
  "retriever": {
    "rule": {
      "match_criteria": {
       "user_query": "hello"
     },
      "ruleset_ids": [
        "vst-curations-sv" // An array of one or more unique query ruleset IDs
      ],
      "retriever": {
        "standard": {
          "query": {
            "match": {
              "tag": "test"
            }
            }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

The query returns all results.


